00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:45.640
how does light impact the way we feel?

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:47.780
So, when I get up in the morning,

00:06:47.780 --> 00:06:49.790
I have the opportunity
to interact with light

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:52.250
in certain ways or to avoid
light in certain ways.

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:54.150
I have the opportunity
to interact with sunlight

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:56.040
or with artificial light.

00:06:56.040 --> 00:07:00.610
Maybe you could just wade us
into what the relationship is

00:07:00.610 --> 00:07:02.670
between light and these things

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:04.120
like mood and hunger, et cetera.

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:05.250
- Sure.

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:08.060
So, I mean, you do appreciate the effect

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:09.130
of light for vision.

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:12.300
So, when you wake up in a beautiful area,

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:15.290
beautiful ocean, light is essential;

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:20.160
the sunrise, the sunset, blue
sky, beautiful mountains.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.180
So, that's your conscious
perception of light,

00:07:23.180 --> 00:07:25.750
but light has a completely
different aspect

00:07:25.750 --> 00:07:28.410
that is independent of conscious vision

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:30.400
or image forming functions.

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:33.420
And that's how it regulates many important

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:34.710
functions in your body.

00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:37.980
I think the best that is
well studied and well known

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:40.020
is your circadian clock.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:42.710
And the word circadian
comes from the word circa,

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:45.250
which is approximate and diem is day.

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:46.620
So, it's an approximate day.

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:48.560
Why is it an approximate day?

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:51.150
Because if I put you or
any other human being

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:54.960
who have a normal circadian
clock in a constant conditions

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:58.940
with no information about
feeding time, about sleep time,

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:01.130
about what time it is outside,

00:08:01.130 --> 00:08:02.920
you still have a daily rhythm,

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:04.860
but it's not exactly 24 hours.

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:08.050
So it will shift out of the solar day

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:09.880
because it's not exactly 24 hours,

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:11.380
and hence the name circadian.

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:13.440
- So, just to ask a quick
question about that.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:17.760
When you say you have
this about 24 hour rhythm,

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.833
how does that rhythm show up
in the tissues of our body?

00:08:22.102 --> 00:08:22.935
- Great question.

00:08:22.935 --> 00:08:26.220
So, it shows up at every
level that we know we studied;

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:28.460
it shows up at the level of the cell.

00:08:28.460 --> 00:08:30.310
It shows up at the level of the tissue,

00:08:30.310 --> 00:08:32.130
and it shows up at your behavior.

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:35.350
The most obvious for you
is your sleep-wake cycle.

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:39.680
You sleep and you're awake and
sleep at the 24 hour rhythms.

00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:42.330
And if you measure the
sleep-wake cycle of humans

00:08:42.330 --> 00:08:44.560
who are maintaining constant conditions,

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:47.040
you will see that the period
length of the sleep rhythm

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:49.640
on average is more than 24 hours.

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:51.860
In humans it's 24.2 hours.

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:55.240
So you'll be drifting .2 hours every day

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:57.550
out of the solar day if
you don't get the sunlight.

00:08:57.550 --> 00:09:01.420
So the sunlight adjusts
that approximate day

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:05.060
to an exact day, so now
your behavior is adjusted

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:08.040
to the light-dark
environment or the solar day.

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:09.640
- Okay, so if I understand correctly,

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:11.390
if I were to go into a cave-

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:12.300
- Yeah.
- Or I would to be

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:14.060
in constant light.
- Yeah.

00:09:14.060 --> 00:09:15.940
- And I didn't close my eyes-
- Yeah.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:19.080
- In constant light,
that I would still sleep

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:21.387
in one coherent about.
- Yes.

00:09:21.387 --> 00:09:23.530
- And I would still be
awake for more or less one

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:25.550
coherent about, maybe a nap.
- Yes.

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:30.550
- But the total duration
of my day, so to speak,

00:09:31.330 --> 00:09:34.390
would be a little bit
longer than 24 hours?

00:09:34.390 --> 00:09:36.940
- Perfect.
- But if I'm in a condition

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:38.657
like most people are where the sun goes up

00:09:38.657 --> 00:09:41.310
and the sun goes down, and
I have some understanding

00:09:41.310 --> 00:09:43.287
of that sunrise and sunset, then-

00:09:43.287 --> 00:09:44.180
- You don't have the understanding,

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:46.620
you don't have to have
conscious understanding.

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:48.247
You have the detection.
- Right.

00:09:48.247 --> 00:09:51.700
- So, circadian photoentrainment
is the word we use,

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:55.300
entraining the circadian clock
to the photic environment

00:09:55.300 --> 00:09:56.960
is completely subconscious.

00:09:56.960 --> 00:09:58.140
You're not aware of it.

00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:00.820
It's not like vision or image forming,

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:02.900
where you actually know
what you're looking at.

00:10:02.900 --> 00:10:05.430
So, it's all hypothalamic.

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:08.580
It's part of the brain that
is not consciously driven.

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:10.780
So, you actually do not
know when it happens

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:11.750
or when it doesn't happen.

